{{Infobox ancient site | name = Aedava | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alternate_name = ''Aedeva'', ''Aedabe'', ''Aedeba'', ''Aedadeba'' | image = Teritoriul onomastic al elementului dava - Sorin Olteanu.jpg | image_size = 165px | alt = | caption = Map of Dacian settlements. | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_size = | iso_region = | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | relief = | coordinates = | map_dot_label = | location = {{BUL}} | area = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = | event = | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = | designation1 = | designation1_number = | designation2 = | designation2_number = | website = | architectural_styles = | architectural_details = | notes = }} '''Aedava''' (also known as '''Aedeva''', '''Aedabe''', '''Aedeba''', '''Aedadeba''') was a [[Dacians|Dacian]] settlement located south of the [[Danube]] in [[Moesia]] (present-day northern [[Bulgaria]]).{{sfn|Grumeza|2009|p=14}}{{sfn|Velkov|1977|p=92}} In his ''[[De Aedificiis]]'', the 6th century AD historian [[Procopius]] placed Aedava on the [[Danubian road]] between [[Augustae]] and [[Variana]].{{sfn|Procopius|550 AD|loc=IV 2,6}}{{sfn|Olteanu|loc=Toponyms}} He also mentioned that Emperor [[Justinian]] (r. 527–565) restored the damaged portion of the town defenses.{{sfn|Procopius|550 AD|loc=IV 2,6}}
