The '''kalumbu''', or '''kalumbo''', is a traditional instrument of the [[Tonga people (Zambia and Zimbabwe)|Tonga]] and [[Ila people|Ila]] people of [[Zambia]] and [[Zimbabwe]]. A single metal-stringed [[Musical bow|bow]] played with a stick is lashed onto a [[calabash]] gourd that acts as a [[Resonance chamber|resonating chamber]]. The kalumbu player manipulates the [[resonance]] of the [[Musical instrument|instrument]] by moving the gourd toward and away from his or her chest. Though now quite rare in [[Africa]], the kalumbu is considered the predecessor of the Afro-Brazilian [[berimbau]] used in [[Capoeira]] performances.<ref>{{cite book|title=World Music: The Rough Guide|author1=Simon Broughton |author2=Mark Ellingham |author3=Richard Trillo |year= 1999|isbn=1-85828-635-2|page=671}}</ref>

A similar instrument, the dende, is played by children in [[Botswana]].

