{{DEFAULTSORT:Travel warning}} [[Category:Travel]] [[Category:International relations]]

In 1968 there was an incident when a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] {{sclass2-|November|submarine}} tracked an American [[Aircraft carrier|carrier]] group traveling at {{convert|31|kn|km/h|lk=in|0}}.<ref> {{cite book | last = Tyler | first = Patrick | authorlink = Patrick_Tyler | coauthors = | title = Running Critical | publisher = Harper&Row | year = 1986 | location = New York | pages = 23–26, 34–46 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}
</ref> This led the [[United States Navy]] to develop the {{sclass-|Los Angeles|submarine|1}}s, whose reported speed is {{convert|30|-|32|kn|km/h|0}}.
[[File:USS Albacore (AGSS-569), launching 1953.jpg|thumb|right|300px|{{USS|Albacore|AGSS-569|6}} with its [[teardrop hull]] claimed {{convert|33|kn|km/h|0}}]]
There are established reports and manufacturer's claims that would indicate two (or perhaps more) submarines are capable of speeds exceeding {{convert|30|kn|km/h|0}}. In 1965, {{USS|Albacore|AGSS-569|6}} reported a speed of {{convert|33|kn|km/h|0}},<ref> {{cite book | last = Tyler | first = Patrick | authorlink = Patrick_Tyler | coauthors = | title = Running Critical | publisher = Harper&Row | year = 1986 | location = New York | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | page = 70 }}</ref> but this was not an official record.<ref>A sightseer's guide to engineering - [http://www.engineeringsights.org/SightDetail.asp?Sightid=565&id=NH&view=s&name=New+Hampshire&page=1&image=0 USS Albacore, Port of Portsmouth Maritime Museum & Albacore Park]</ref> The {{sclass-|Akula|submarine|5}} (Russian: ''shark'')-class vessel is reportedly capable of travelling submerged at {{convert|35|kn|km/h|0}}, its predecessor, the {{sclass-|Alfa|submarine|4}}, could attain short speed bursts of {{convert|40|-|45|kn|km/h|0}} while submerged.<ref> {{cite book | last = Tyler | first = Patrick | authorlink = Patrick_Tyler | coauthors = | title = Running Critical | publisher = Harper&Row | year = 1986 | location = New York | pages = 152–153 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last = Nilsen | first = Thomas | authorlink = | last2 = Kudrik | first2 = Igor | last3 = Nikitin | first3 = Alexandr | work = Bellona Report | title = Project 705, 705 K (Lira) - Alfa Class | date = 1997-09-28 | url = http://spb.org.ru/bellona/ehome/russia/nfl/705.htm | accessdate = | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> There are claims that the Russian titanium submarine ''[[Soviet submarine K-222|K-162]]'' reached {{convert|44.7|kn|km/h|0}} on [[sea trial]]s, fully submerged, in 1969. However, due to the rather secretive nature of these vessels, confirmations of these numbers are not present.
The British [[Spearfish torpedo]] designed to counter high-speed Russian submarines, such as the ''Alfa''-class submarine, is reputed to have a speed in excess of {{convert|70|kn|km/h|0}}. The Russian rocket-powered [[Supercavitation|supercavitating]] torpedo [[VA-111 Shkval]] is reportedly capable of speed in excess of {{convert|200|kn|km/h}}.<ref name="periscope">{{cite web|title=VA-111 Shkval Torpedo|url=http://www.militaryperiscope.com/mdb-smpl/weapons/minetorp/torpedo/w0004768.shtml|work=www.militaryperiscope.com|accessdate=December 1, 2010}}</ref> [[Germany|German]] press reports of an underwater anti-torpedo missile named Barracuda that allegedly reaches {{convert|800|km/h|kn|order=flip}}.<ref>''Highspeed in der Tiefe'' {{cite web |url=http://www.morgenwelt.de/609.1.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-09-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928005558/http://www.morgenwelt.de/609.1.html |archivedate=2007-09-28 |df= }} Morgenwelt: Superkavitation June 23, 2005 '''Translation needed from German'''</ref> The United States Navy has contracted with the [[General Dynamics Electric Boat]] Division to support development of the Underwater Express, an undersea transport capable of controllable speeds up to {{convert|100|kn|km/h|0}} through supercavitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gdeb.com/news/2006archives.html|title=General Dynamics Electric Boat Press Releases - 2006|publisher=General Dynamics Electric Boat}}</ref>
